post_text:
To the parents of students in grades K - 3:

We are reaching out to inform you that our Chromebook shipment scheduled to arrive in August has been delayed until mid-October. As such, we are unable to provide a Chromebook to your child for Thursday and Friday remote instruction. We will assign one as soon as our shipment arrives.

We are asking that you use your own personal device in the meantime, just as you did last March through June. You can access instruction using your cell phone or any other personal computing device you may have access to.

Should you have any concerns regarding lack of access to a device, please contact your child‚Äôs teacher immediately. Thank you for your patience and understanding. Thank you.

WBCS Administration

post_text: We thought you may want to "see" what using alternate space as classrooms would like like at WBCS. The images below show the Gymnasium being used as 4 classrooms should we need them. The standard classroom setup (both regular classrooms and annex classrooms) will include enough desks and chairs for students placed in rows and 6 feet apart, a teacher work station, and a white board. Furniture will be kept to a minimum. There will not be areas for students to gather at tables and/or on carpets and no small group space. They will however be print-rich and as colorful as possible.

Hi All!

In staying true to our word to share what we know about reopening when we know it-- here is today's update.

The New York State Education Department today presented the framework of guidance to help schools and school districts as they plan to reopen, whether that occurs in person, remotely, or in a combination of the two. In addition to the framework presented today, formal guidance will be disseminated later this week that will enable New York‚Äôs schools to continue to safely educate their students this fall.

The formal guidance is expected to be released on Wednesday. We will continue to update you.

One step at a time...

-Mrs. Todoro

Waiting is the hardest part...but here is what we know today:

The NYS Education Department will issue guidance on July 13th.

Governor Cuomo announced today that he will review the Education Department's guidance and issue a final decision on reopening of schools during the first week of August.

In the meantime, the WBCS Reopening Task Force has been formed, will meet in mid-July, and will plan for whatever comes our way!!!!

Stay tuned.

Good Morning,

As we stated yesterday, WBCS is committed to supporting our WBCS families in any way possible. We will continue to share resources for powerful, age-appropriate discussions for families and teachers. We encourage you to use the resources below to have engaging dialogue with your child. Faculty and staff will continue to review guidance and resources as well and will hold class discussions in an age-appropriate manner.

Please feel free to reach out to our Social Worker, Ms. Hinke, your child's classroom teacher, or any member of the WBCS team for any additional support or assistance.

https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/05/31/how-talk-kids-racism-racial-violence-police-brutality/5288065002/

Q & A style article with questions that many parents and teachers might be having right now.
https://www.tolerance.org/sites/default/files/general/beyond_golden_rule.pdf

Teaching Tolerance is an amazing resource. This article is focused on the issues of race and prejudice and how children are impacted at different age levels.

post_text:
If your child/children receive free or reduced-price school lunches, then they are eligible to receive P-EBT food benefits for the days their school was closed due to COVID-19 (March ‚Äì June, $420 in P-EBT benefits per child). This includes all children attending Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) schools where all children receive free or reduced-price school lunches even if the family does not qualify based on income. Since WBCS is a CEP school, all students are eligible for this benefit. Begin checking your mail for this P-EBT notice beginning in mid-June.

Follow this link for more details on eligibility and payment: https://otda.ny.gov/SNAP-COVID-19/Frequently-Asked-Questions-Pandemic-EBT.asp

Dear WBCS Families,

I promised I would share ANY news I heard with you, so I thought I'd pass this along:

Today, Governor Cuomo announced that summer school will not open for in-person instruction this year and that all summer instruction will continue remotely.

The Governor has not yet made a decision regarding the upcoming fall semester. However, he stated that schools will be required to submit their Fall re-opening plans in July and that guidance for developing those plans will be released in early June.

WBCS eagerly awaits the Governor's guidance as it will assist us in making any plans for Fall 2020!!!! Stay tuned...

-Mrs. Todoro

post_text:
Dear WBCS Families-

Lately, I‚Äôve been feeling like I‚Äôm a bit stuck. Stuck in the house because it‚Äôs freezing. Stuck in the same routine day after day. Stuck waiting for guidance on what school should look like in Fall 2020.

I‚Äôm sure you feel It, too. But...I‚Äôm trusting the wait. I‚Äôm embracing the uncertainty, although as someone who likes control, it‚Äôs not a very comfortable feeling. I‚Äôm eager and excited to plan for whatever the future may hold.

Why am I excited at a time like this? Because some day in the future (I‚Äôm not exactly sure when) we WILL be together again. And that will be a beautiful thing! The future is ours. The possibilities endless.

Hang in there! Waiting is hard. I understand. When we know something more about next school year you will be the first to know. I promise.

We got this!

Mrs. Todoro

post_text:
Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!!!!

A special note for all of the amazing teachers at WBCS!!!
.
Dear WBCS Teachers,

We know your work is never done and your day (even when virtual) never ends. There are still lessons to plan, assignments to grade, and "meetings" to attend.

Now that your home has become your classroom, your whiteboard is now a Chromeboook and your students, who wish they could see you in person and hug you, are miles away--you continue to do an AMAZING job. We are so lucky to have you.

So, thank you for the lessons. For inventing new ways (in an instant) to keep your students engaged, and for making a difference in our lives. This week we celebrate YOU and all that you are doing.

Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!

Love,
Mrs. Todoro, Mrs. Sterns, Mrs. Banas, Mr. Siddall, & Mrs. Lysiak

post_text:
And there we have it....

We will not be returning this school year. My gut told me it was coming, but I have to be honest it was like a stab to the heart when I officially heard it. It hurts. It's frustrating. It's not ideal, but we will be back stronger than ever. I promise that!

So what does this mean for WBCS? It means we will continue what we are doing. We will continue to put our students' learning and social-emotional needs first. We will continue remote instruction until the end of June. We will have "reimagined" classroom celebrations, moving up days, and graduation ceremonies.

We will finish this year strong regardless if it's via technology.

Stay tuned for more details, but for right now I need to wrap up this ugly crying and catch my breath.

We got this, WBCS!

- Mrs. Todoro

post_text:
Hi WBCS Family!

As we wrap up Week #3 does anyone else feel like this week was 356 days long? Maybe it's because it rained half of the week or that it's been days since we have seen each other. Here's the good news---this won't last forever. We will be together again some day. We will get through this...together. There's no doubt in my mind---WBCS is one TOUGH team. We got this:)

-Mrs. Todoro

post_text:
The safety of our students is a top priority at West Buffalo Charter School. Please note the following morning drop off information:

Students can be dropped off on Lafayette Ave. from 7:15 am-8:00 am. Please pull up on the same side of the school, so that your child does NOT need to cross the street. This can be very dangerous, as there is a lot of morning traffic on Lafayette. Also, this is a "drop and go" location. Cars should pull up, allow students to get out, and pull away. If you need to park for any reason, please park on Barton side of the building and come in.

Please refrain from making U-Turns on Lafayette as it is illegal. Again, students should be dropped off on the school side of Lafayette only.

You can also utilize the Barton side of the building for drop off , as well. Adults are present outside from 7:50 am -8:00 am to assist students into the building.
text:
The safety of our students is a top priority at West Buffalo Charter School. Please note the following morning drop off information:

Students can be dropped off on Lafayette Ave. from 7:15 am-8:00 am. Please pull up on the same side of the school, so that your child does NOT need to cross the street. This can be very dangerous, as there is a lot of morning traffic on Lafayette. Also, this is a "drop and go" location. Cars should pull up, allow students to get out, and pull away. If you need to park for any reason, please park on Barton side of the building and come in.

Please refrain from making U-Turns on Lafayette as it is illegal. Again, students should be dropped off on the school side of Lafayette only.

You can also utilize the Barton side of the building for drop off , as well. Adults are present outside from 7:50 am -8:00 am to assist students into the building.

Arrival - A student who arrives late (after 8:00 AM) and will be marked tardy. Students arriving after 8:00 AM must report to the Main Office with a parent/guardian and an excuse to be signed in.

The Lafayette doors are only open from 7:15 AM- 8:00 AM. This area is for drop off only, please do not park in this lane. Also, please do not have your child cross Lafayette in the morning as it can be busy.

Staff will be located on Barton and Lafayette from 7:50 am - 8:00 am to assist students out of the cars. If you need to come into the building, please park (not in front of the school) and come in.

Thank you!

Would your child like to learn how to skate for FREE?

WBCS students are invited to attend free lessons through Hasek's Heroes.

This FREE program will provide participants (grades 4 and up) with lessons on the following: how to use the mountain bike park (by WNY Mountain Bike Association), recycling, and basic financial tools (by Five Star Bank). We will provide bikes and safety gear for children to use.

Transportation must be provided by the family to the Bike Park: 825 Fuhrmann Blvd ., Buffalo NY 14203.

Time: 12:00 - 2:00 Must arrive at least 15 minutes early

Sign up at the link below:

WGRZ.COM
Meet the kids behind the 2019 WNY Invention Convention

Western New York Invention Convention
May 17, 2019 at 7:31 AM ¬∑

WGRZ - Channel 2, Buffalo did a nice profile on the inventors and the event itself! The first inventor is from Our Lady of Black Rock School and the 3 brothers, while they did their whole project from home, are from PS 64 Frederick Law Olmsted School. Max, who is the brother who invented "Night Sight" is one of the delegates attending 2019 National Invention Convention NICEE along with David from West Buffalo Charter School who invented the "Manual Game System". https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/meet-the-kids-behind-the-2019-wny-invention-convention/71-9bdea86e-0404-4790-be7f-0eabdf81d20d

post_text:
Congratulations to our WBCS students who participated in the Invention Convention this weekend!

David and Joshua won first place and are on their way to Nationals later this month. They also were awarded as Inventors of the Year!

Nola and Kameron took home 2nd place for their grade and division!

Our school also won a 3-D printer!

We are so proud of all who participated! We can't wait to see what Nationals bring!
